'''都怒我阿羅斯等''' (つぬがあらしと, birth and death dates unknown) is a figure recorded in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}''. He is described as an ancient Korean individual and is said to be the son of the king of the {{ill|Gaya Kingdom|ja|加羅国|12=draft|12=draft}}.
In the ''Nihon Shoki'', his name is rendered as "都怒我阿羅斯等", while other texts offer variations such as "都怒賀阿羅斯止", "都怒何阿羅斯志止", and "都奴加阿羅斯志等". The Nihon Shoki also provides his alias as "'''于斯岐阿利叱智干岐''' (うしきありしちかんき)".
He was a prince of the {{ill|Gaya Kingdom|ja|加羅国|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Daigaya/Daikara, a country in what is now southern Korea) and is said to be the eponymous figure from whom the place name {{ill|Tsuruga City|ja|敦賀市|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tsuruga) derives.
== Records == According to the ''Nihon Shoki'', two traditions are recorded in a marginal note in the entry for the 2nd year of the reign of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Sfn|坂本|平野|2010}}</ref>
The first tradition states that during the era of {{ill|Emperor Sujin|ja|崇神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tsunuga Arashito—described as having horns growing from his forehead—arrived by ship from {{ill|Anamune|ja|穴門|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Nagato Province|ja|長門国|12=draft|12=draft}}, via {{ill|Izumo Province|ja|出雲国|12=draft|12=draft}}, to {{ill|Kusei-ura|ja|笥飯浦|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Sfn|坂本|平野|2010}}</ref> This is said to be the origin of the term "角鹿" (horned deer), which later evolved into "敦賀".
The second tradition relates that when Arashito was in his own country, a white stone obtained as compensation for a yellow ox transformed into a beautiful maiden. Arashito then sought to unite with her (a practice referred to as "まぐわい"), but the maiden left his presence and went to Japan, where she became the deity of the Himiyoso-sha at Nanba and in the former district of Toyokuni in {{ill|Toyokuni|ja|豊国|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Sfn|坂本|平野|2010}}</ref> Related traditions reminiscent of this account are also found in the legend of the "Ameno Hiboko" (天之日槍) and the tale of {{ill|Agaryū Hime no Kami|ja|阿加流比売神|12=draft|12=draft}}, as well as in excerpts from the ''Settsu Fudoki'' cited in the ''Man'yōshū'' commentaries.<ref name="谷川1999">{{Cite book |和書 |author=谷川健一 |author-link=谷川健一 |title=日本の神々 |publisher=[[岩波書店]] |series=[[岩波新書]] 618 |date=1999-06 |isbn=4-00-430618-3 |pages=180-186}}</ref>
== Descendant Clans == In the ''{{ill|Shinsen Seishiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}}'', the following clans are listed as his descendants:<ref>{{Sfn|福井県|1993a}}</ref> * Sakyō Shobana Ōichikubi – said to be descended from Tsunuga Arasudome. * Sakyō Shobana Shimizu-kubi – said to be descended from Tsunuga Arashishi. * Yamato Province Shobana Hikata-kubi – said to be descended from Tsunuga Arashitome.
